Udacity Data Analyst Nanodegree¶

Act Report¶

Project 4: WeRateDogs Twitter Analysis - Data Wrangling - Gater, asses, clean and analyse tweets about dog ratings¶

What its all about:
The dataset that you will be wrangling (and analyzing and visualizing) is the tweet archive of Twitter user @dog_rates, also known as WeRateDogs. WeRateDogs is a Twitter account that rates people's dogs with a humorous comment about the dog. These ratings almost always have a denominator of 10. The numerators, though? Almost always greater than 10. 11/10, 12/10, 13/10, etc. Why? Because "they're good dogs Brent." WeRateDogs has over 4 million followers and has received international media 'coverage. WeRateDogs downloaded their Twitter archive and sent it to Udacity via email exclusively for you to use in this project. This archive contains basic tweet data (tweet ID, timestamp, text, etc.) for all 5000+ of their tweets as they stood on August 1, 2017.

(cited from Udacity, on January 24, 2021)

  1. How does the distribution of retweets and likes look like?

  3. Who are the top rated dogs?

>Key findings As we can see from the three plots above golden retriever with a large head start the the most often predicted dogs, followed with a huge distance by labrador retrievers and pembrokes. Without considering the amount of these predictions, the 30 top rated dogs are visualised in the second figure: Dumbers are with a hugh distance the best rated dogs (with a ratio of above 2.5 (from the self created rating column)). However this might be biased, as it could have been only one very cute dog that got this rating. Therefore, for the third and last plot I only selected dog breeds that have been predicted at least 15 times or more. We can then see that the top rated dog breed no longer is dumber, but pomeranian.¶

To conclude, here are some cute pomerians. No surprise, they recieve the first place ...
